{'abstract': 'JERUSALEM: With the Arab uprising against the Jewish colonization of Palestine spreading from town to country, the British authorities are faced with a veritable revolt, which, it is now foreseen, can only be suppressed by the use of force on a large scal', 'web_url': 'https://www.nytimes.com/2004/08/28/IHT-1929revolt-in-palestine-in-our-pages100-75-and-50-years-ago.html', 'snippet': 'JERUSALEM: With the Arab uprising against the Jewish colonization of Palestine spreading from town to country, the British authorities are faced with a veritable revolt, which, it is now foreseen, can only be suppressed by the use of force on a la...', 'lead_paragraph': 'JERUSALEM: With the Arab uprising against the Jewish colonization of Palestine spreading from town to country, the British authorities are faced with a veritable revolt, which, it is now foreseen, can only be suppressed by the use of force on a large scale. Troops are being rushed to the storm centres, but owing to the lack of communications, no sooner is one attack dealt with than another begins elsewhere. The situation is admittedly serious and today [Aug. 27] the Consuls of all nations held a meeting to urge the British authorities to take stringent measures to protect their nationals. Although no doubt is expressed that order will eventually be restored, it is admitted that this may take some time owing to the countryside character which the uprising has taken. {'abstract': ' JERUSALEM: With the Arab uprising against the Jewish colonization of Palestine spreading from town to country, the British authorities are faced with a veritable revolt, which, it is now foreseen, can only be suppressed by the use of force on a large scale. Troops are being rushed to the storm centres, but owing to the lack of communications, no sooner is one attack dealt with than another begins elsewhere. The situation is admittedly serious and today [Aug. 27] the Consuls of all nations held a meeting to urge the British authorities to take stringent measures to protect their nationals. Although no doubt is expressed that order will eventually be restored, it is admitted that this may take some time owing to the countryside character which the uprising has taken. Several more warships carrying troops and airplanes are reported to have arrived at Jaffa, and today two British battalions and several contingents of armed sailors and marines were dispatched in haste to the storm centres. Airplanes are also reconnoitering and landing troops wherever urgently needed. {'abstract': "  Secretary of State Alexander M. Haig Jr. said today that he had obtained President Hosni Mubarak's agreement for an intensified effort in coming months to achieve a breakthrough in the negotiations with Israel on Palestinian self-rule in the West Bank and the Gaza Strip.   In a 90-minute meeting at Mr. Mubarak's office in Oruba Palace, Mr. Haig was reported to have said that the United States believed Egypt and Israel had spent enough time over the last 20 months inconclusively discussing the issues and that he was ready to give his attention to helping them accelerate their efforts for an agreement.   Kamal Hassan Ali, Egypt's Foreign Minister, told reporters later, ''Our view is that we welcome the participation of Secretary Haig in the process because we feel that it will push forward the negotiations for the autonomy.'' Haig to Meet With Begin   Mr. Haig flies to Israel on Thursday to confer with Prime Minister Menachem Begin and Foreign Minister Yitzhak Shamir on their reaction to his plans for pushing the negotiations forward.
